revision.text:
'''Anthelioi''' ({{lang-grc|Ἀνθήλιοι δαίμονες}}) or '''Antelii''' or '''Anthelii''' were certain divinities whose images stood before the doors of houses,<ref name="tert">{{cite book | last =[[Tertullian]] | title =The Selected Works of Tertullian | publisher =Library of Alexandria | series =Library of Alexandria | volume =1 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=4X9dAQAAQBAJ | isbn = 9781465588432 | accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref> and were exposed to the sun, from which they derived their name,<ref>[[Aeschylus]], ''Agamemnon'' 530</ref><ref>[[Christian Lobeck]], ''On the Ajax of Sophocles'' 805</ref> which is literally "gods that face the sun".<ref name="alchemy">{{cite book | editor-last =Cheak | editor-first =Aaron | title =Alchemical Traditions: From Antiquity to the Avant-Garde | publisher =Numen Books | date =2013 | pages =148 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=jUSwAQAAQBAJ | isbn = 9780987559821 | accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref> The sun conceptually was to animate the statues with its [[pneuma]].<ref name="alchemy"/>

These deities were similar in character to a number of other gateway-gods, including [[Cardea]], and Apollo under the epithet [[Thyraeus|Apollo Thyraeus]], protector of doorways.<ref name="tert"/>

