{{refimprove|date=April 2018}} [[File:Philppine air (873989542).jpg|300px|thumbnail|Travellers stand in line for a flight to the Philippines carrying balikbayan boxes. ]] A '''balikbayan box''' (literally "repatriate box") is a [[corrugated box]] containing items sent by [[overseas Filipino]]s (known as "[[balikbayan]]s"). Though often shipped by [[freight forwarder]]s specializing in balikbayan boxes by sea, such boxes can be brought by Filipinos returning to the [[Philippines]] by air.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mandalit |last=del Barco |authorlink=Mandalit Del Barco |author= |coauthors= |title=Gift Boxes Help Migrant Filipinos Keep Ties to Home |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5066964 |format=radio |work=Morning Edition |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |id= |pages= |page= |date=2005-12-23 |accessdate= |language= |quote= }}</ref>
==History== The balikbayan box arose around the 1980s in the [[United States]] brought about by the influx of [[overseas Filipino worker]]s in the country. The first [[freight forwarder]] to offer balikbayan box services was Rico Nunga who started REN International in [[Los Angeles, California]] in 1981.<ref name=LAT2018 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://renbalikbayan.wordpress.com/about/ |title=About Us |publisher=REN International |accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> The following year, Ramon Ungco, a [[Filipinos|Filipino]] residing in [[New York City]], founded Port Jersey Shipping International.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portjerseyshipping.com/about_us |title=About Us |publisher=Port Jersey Shipping |accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> These two companies are considered the pioneers of [[door-to-door]] delivery of balikbayan boxes, which back then were charged import duties upon arrival in the [[Philippines]].{{fact|date=April 2018}}
On 30 June 1987, then [[President of the Philippines|Philippine President]] [[Corazon Aquino]] enacted Executive Order No. 206.<ref name=LAT2018 /><ref name=EO206>{{cite web |url=http://www.lawphil.net/executive/execord/eo1987/eo_206_1987.html |title=Executive Order No. 206 |work=Amending Section 105 of the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines |publisher=LawPhil.net |accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> This order amended Section 105 (f) and added a new subsection (f-1) to Republic Act No. 1937, also known as the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines, which was signed into law on 22 July 1957 by former president [[Carlos P. Garcia]].<ref name=RA1937>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.ph/1957/06/22/republic-act-no-1937/ |title=Republic Act No. 1937 |work=An Act to Revise and Codify the Tariff and Customs Laws of the Philippines |publisher=Official Gazette of the Philippines |accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref>
The amended Section 105 of the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines provides duty- and tax-free privileges to balikbayan boxes sent to the Philippines by [[overseas Filipinos|overseas Filipino workers]] (OFWs) as recognition of the magnitude of their contribution and sacrifices in foreign lands as well as bringing of a considerable amounts of foreign exchange annually that contributed to the national recovery effort at that time.<ref name=EO206/> This allowed tax-free entry of personal goods in the country from Filipinos overseas. People then began sending balikbayan boxes through friends and co-workers who were returning to the Philippines.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
After the [[September 11 attacks]] in the US and the passage of the [[Patriot Act]] by the [[US Congress]], balikbayan boxes have been subjected to rigorous inspections by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s Out-Bound Exam Team that caused massive delays of up to three weeks at the [[US Customs]] inspection facility. This extended shipping time from 21 days to 30 plus days. The inspections also resulted in opened balikbayan boxes and complaints of [[pilferage]] and mishandling. The [[Bureau of Customs (Philippines)|Bureau of Customs]] also conducts 100% inspections that added to the burden of delayed shipments. The inspections are the result of some unscrupulous individuals who use balikbayan boxes to smuggle commercial items without paying taxes or smuggle [[contraband]]. Since balikbayan box shipping is a consolidated shipment, even one illegal item will affect all 400 or so packages inside the container. The inspection process has been modernized with the installation of high performance X-ray machines.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
In 2012, these delays were further aggravated by the decision of the [[City of Manila]] to impose a truck ban along the route to and from the [[Port of Manila]], causing backlogs in releasing and transporting not only balikbayan boxes but all cargoes, domestic and international. Most balikbayan box companies, which are based in [[Parañaque City]] near the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|airport]], were heavily affected by the truck ban until it was resolved.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
The industry was scrutinized by the Philippine Senate in 2015 after mounting complaints were brought to the attention of the public through social media after the Philippine Customs Commissioner Albert Lina announced the opening of balikbayan boxes for inspection and additional taxes to be imposed.{{fact|date=April 2018}} The inquiry brought the passage of the Customs Modernization Act, which had been pending for years, and the inclusion of the Balikbayan Box Law in the act, increasing the tax-exemption ceiling from PHP 500 to PHP 150,000. This included items being brought home by Filipino tourists from trips abroad, pasalubong or gifts, and returning resident shipments.<ref>http://www.sra.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/RA-10863_Customs-Tariff_Modernization_act.pdf</ref>
To protect consumers, the [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] (DTI), through its Philippine Shipper's Bureau, conducts regular accreditation of international freight forwarders and discourages consumers from patronizing unaccredited and incredibly cheap shipping companies.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
According to the Door to Door Consolidated Association of the Philippines, there are 400,000 balikbayan boxes that arrive in the Philippines every month.<ref name=LAT2018>{{cite news |last=Shyong |first=Frank |date=28 April 2018 |title=These boxes are a billion-dollar industry of homesickness for Filipinos overseas |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-balikbayan-boxes-20180428-htmlstory.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=28 April 2018 }}</ref>
==Description== Balikbayan boxes may contain items the sender thinks the recipient would like, regardless of whether those items can be bought cheaply in the Philippines, such as non-perishable food, toiletries, household items, electronics, toys, designer clothing, or items difficult to find in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phuong |last=Ly |authorlink= |author= |coauthors= |title=Money Is Not Enough at Christmas |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A23376-2004Dec23 |format= |work=Washington Post |publisher= |id= |pages= |page=B05 |date=2004-12-24 |accessdate= |language= |quote= }}</ref> A balikbayan box intended for air travel is designed to conform to [[Luggage#Commercial airlines|airline luggage restrictions]] and many Filipino stores sell them. Some boxes come with a cloth cover and side handles. Others are tightly secured with tape or rope, and thus not confused with an ordinary moving box that is lightly wrapped.
The balikbayan boxes come in three standard sizes:<ref name=dimensionsinfo>{{cite web|title=Balikbayan Box Dimensions|url=http://www.dimensionsinfo.com/balikbayan-box-dimensions/|work=Dimensions Info: Because Size Matters|publisher=Memebridge.com|accessdate=21 March 2013|quote=There are three types of balikbayan box, namely the medium box, the large or the regular box and the extra large box. The width and height of the medium box is 18 inches while the depth is 16 inches. The standard width of the large box has a width and depth of 18 inches while the height is 24 inches. The extra large box has a width of width and height of 24 inches while its depth is 18 inches.}}</ref> * Medium: 18 x 16 x 18 inches * Large: 18 x 18 x 24 inches * Extra large: 24 x 18 x 24 inches
Shipped boxes are delivered directly to the recipient, usually the family of the overseas Filipino.
==Cultural significance== Part of the attraction of the balikbayan box is its economic value, as it allows cheaper bulk shipment of items versus sending each individually or in smaller boxes through postal services. The tradeoff though is longer transit time by [[container ship]], which typically requires several weeks, along with the lack of a firm delivery date. The balikbayan box is a modern manifestation of the general Philippine practice of ''[[pasalubong]]'', where travellers within or outside the country are culturally expected to bring home gifts to family, friends and colleagues.{{fact|date=April 2018}} the balikbayan box provides connections between family within the Philippines and those who are abroad, and provide goods for the family within the Philippines.<ref name=LAT2018 />
