{{distinguish|Electronic publishing}} {{unreferenced|date=September 2014}} [[Image:Webpage.png|thumb|200px|A screenshot of a web page. The computers to store, transmit, and display the web page are electronic media. The web page is an electronic medium.]] [[Image:Pcm.svg|200px|thumb|right|Graphical representations of electrical audio data. Electronic media uses either analog (red) or digital (blue) signal processing.]]
'''Electronic media''' are [[media (communication)|media]] that use [[electronics]] or [[electromechanical]] [[audience]] to access the content. This is in contrast to static media (mainly [[printing|print]] media), which today are most often [[Desktop publishing|created electronically]], but do not require electronics to be accessed by the end user in the printed form. The primary electronic media sources familiar to the general public are [[video]] recordings, [[sound recording and reproduction|audio recordings]], [[multimedia]] presentations, [[Presentation program|slide presentations]], [[CD-ROM]] and [[online and offline|online]] content. Most [[new media]] are in the form of [[digital media]]. However, electronic media may be in either [[analogue electronics]] [[data]] or [[digital electronics|digital electronic]] [[digital data|data]] format.
Although the term is usually associated with content recorded on a [[Data storage device|storage medium]], recordings are not required for live [[broadcasting]] and online networking.
Any equipment used in the [[telecommunication|electronic communication]] process (e.g. [[television]], [[Receiver (radio)|radio]], [[telephone]], [[desktop computer]], [[game console]], [[handheld device]]) may also be considered electronic media.
== History of development == {| width="65%" |- valign=top |width="50%"| * '''[[Transmission (telecommunications)|Transmission]]''' ** '''''[[Wire]] and [[transmission line]]s''''' *** [[Electromagnetic telegraph|Telegraph]] 1795–1832 *** [[Fax|Facsimile]] 1843–1861 *** [[Telephone]] 1849–1877 *** [[Coaxial cable]] 1880 *** [[Fiber Optics]] 1956–1970 **'''''[[Wireless]]''''' *** [[Radio]] 1897–1920 *** [[Satellite communications|Satellite]] 1958–1972 *** [[Free space optics|Free Space Optics]] 1960s **'''''[[Internet]]''''' *** [[Download]]ing 1969 (first [[Communications protocol|protocols]] for [[List of file transfer protocols|transferring files]]) *** [[streaming media|Live Streaming]] 1996 ([[Real-time Transport Protocol|RTP]] protocol) * '''[[Comparison of display technology|Display]] and [[Output device|output]]''' ** [[Information Processing]] 1940s ([[Technical term|Term]]) ** [[Galvanometer]] 18 ** [[Telegraph sounder|Telegraph Sounder]] 1844 ** [[Telephone|Telephone Receiver]] 1849–1877 ** [[Light red]] 1801–1883 ** [[Neon]] 1893–1902 ** [[Teleprinter]] 1910 ** [[Cathode ray tube|CRT]] 1922 ** [[Tuner (radio)|Radio/television tuner]] 1894–1927 ** [[Loudspeaker|Speaker]]/[[Headphones]] 1876–1928/1930s ** [[LED]]/[[LCD]] 1955–1962/1968 ** [[Laser lighting display|Laser light show]] 1970s ** [[Computer monitor|Computer Monitor]] 1950s/1976 (for [[Personal Computer|PC]]s) ** [[Jumbotron|Large Electronic Display]] 1985 ** [[HDTV]] 1936 ([[Technical term|Term]]) 1990s ([[Standards organization|Standard]]s) ** [[Head mounted display|HMD]] 1968–current |width="50%"| * '''[[Signal (electrical engineering)|Electrical Signal Processing]]''' ** [[Sensor|Capture]] 1745 ([[Capacitor]]) ** [[Analog signal|Analog]] methods of [[code|Encoding]] 1830s ([[Morse code]]) ** [[Modulation|Electronic Modulating]] 1832–1927 ** [[Multiplexing|Electronic Multiplexing]] 1853 ([[Time-division multiplexing|TDM]]) ** [[Digitizing]] 1903 ([[Pulse code modulation|PCM telephone]]) ** [[Enc