The '''International Composers’ Guild''' was an organization created in 1921 by [[Edgard Varèse]] and [[Carlos Salzedo]]. It was responsible for performances and premieres of works by [[Béla Bartók]], [[Alban Berg]], [[Erik Satie]], [[Carlos Chávez]], [[Henry Cowell]], [[Charles Ives]], [[Maurice Ravel]], [[Wallingford Riegger]], [[Francis Poulenc]], and [[Anton von Webern]], and others.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anon|title=Edgard Varèse|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Edgard-Varese#ref159180|website=Encyclopædia Britannica|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>

