{{italic title}} [[File:Njai by Meessen, c 1867.jpg|thumb|[[Hand-colouring of photographs|Hand-tinted]] photograph of a ''njai'' by [[Jacobus Anthonie Meessen]], {{circa}} 1867. He described the concubines as a "necessary evil".{{sfn|Boom|Wachlin|2004}}]] The '''''njai''''' ({{IPA-id|ɲai|}}; [[EYD|Perfected Spelling]]: '''''nyai''''') were women who were kept as housekeepers, companions, and [[concubines]] in the [[Dutch East Indies]] (modern-day Indonesia). In the original [[Balinese language|Balinese]], the word ''njai'' meant "sister",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jacobs|first1=Hans|last2=Roelands|first2=Jan|title=Indisch ABC|year=1970|publisher=Arbeiderspers|language=Dutch|page=103}}</ref> but the term later took a more specific meaning.<ref>{{cite book|title=Indische letteren: documentatieblad van de Werkgroep Indisch-Nederlandse Letterkunde|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PydcAAAAMAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Werkgroep Indisch-Nederlandse Letterkunde|language=Dutch|page=135}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Indisch letterland: verhalen uit twee eeuwen Nederlands- Indische literatuur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bh_iAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Sijthoff|isbn=9789021838014|language=Dutch|page=6}}</ref> Author [[Rob Nieuwenhuys]] described the position of the njai as always subservient, being the white man's housekeeper and companion, before she was his concubine.<ref>{{cite book|last=Berg|first=Joop van den|title=Soebatten, sarongs en sinjo's: Indische woorden in het Nederlands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JHLlAAAAMAAJ|year=1992|publisher=BZZTôH|isbn=9789062915590|language=Dutch|page=62}}</ref>
==Terminology and description== The word ''njai'' (also ''nyai'', ''njaie'', ''nyaie'', ''nyahi'' or ''nyi'') comes from a [[Balinese language|Balinese]] word meaning sister.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jacobs|first1=Hans|last2=Roelands|first2=Jan|title=Indisch ABC|year=1970|publisher=Arbeiderspers|language=Dutch|page=103}}</ref> In [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] the term ''nyai'' refer to "miss" or young woman,<ref>{{cite web | title = Nyai (Sunda - Indonesia)| work = Kamus Daerah | url = http://www.kamusdaerah.com/?bhs=m&bhs2=a&q=nona }}</ref> while in [[Betawi language|Betawi dialect]], ''nyai'' refer to "grandmother" or elderly lady.<ref>{{cite web | title = Nyai (Betawi - Indonesia)| work = Kamus Daerah | url = http://www.kamusdaerah.com/?bhs=f&bhs2=a&q=nyai }}</ref> The ''[[Great Dictionary of the Indonesian Language of the Language Center]]'' gives three definitions for ''njai'': as a term for referring to a married or unmarried woman, as a term for referring to a woman older than the speaker, and for the concubine of a non-Indonesian.<ref>{{cite book|title=Kamus Besar Bahasa Indonesia |trans-title=Great Dictionary of the Indonesian Language |page=971 |edition=4th |language=Indonesian |publisher=Gramedia |location=Jakarta |author=National Department of Education |isbn=978-979-22-3841-9}}</ref> It is this last definition which is used here, a definition which gained traction in the 17th century when [[Balinese people|Balinese]] ''njais'' first became common in the colonial capital of Batavia (now [[Jakarta]]).{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=58}} The word, in discussion of the Indies, is sometimes simply translated as "mistress".<ref>{{cite book|last=Bonneff|first=Marcel|title=L'Indonésie contemporaine vue par ses intellectuels: un choix d'articles de la revue Prisma (1971-1991)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pPdHAAAAMAAJ|year=1994|publisher=L'Harmattan|language=French|isbn=9782738426680}}</ref>
A variety of other terms were used to refer to the ''njai'', with a varying degree of positive and negative connotations. In the 19th century the term ''inlandse huishoudster'', or simply ''huishoudster'' (housekeeper), was common. The ''njai'' were also known as ''moentji'', from the Dutch [[diminutive]] ''mondje'', meaning "mouth", and the more negative ''snaar'' ("[[String (music)|strings]]"); both referred to the ''njai'''s verbal propensities. As the ''njai'' could also serve as a translator and language teacher, terms such as ''boek'' ("book") and ''woordenbooek'' ("dictionary") are also noted. Objectification of the ''njai'' was found in terms such as ''meubel'' ("furniture") and ''inventarisstuk'' ("inventory items").{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=58–59}}
Not all ''njai'' were necessarily native Indonesian--in [[Madelon Szekely-Lulofs]]'s 1931 novel ''[[Rubber (1931 novel)|Rubber]]'', ''njai'' Kiku San is Japanese.<ref name="Meijer">{{cite book|last=Meijer|first=Maaike|title=In tekst gevat: Inleiding tot een kritiek van representatie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PhrOziMoJrkC&pg=PA132|year=2006|publisher=Amsterdam UP|isbn=9789053568552|language=Dutch|page=132}}</ref>
==History== Europeans first arrived in the [[Indonesian archipelago]] in the 16th century, and in 1602 the [[Dutch East India Company]] was established to ensure Dutch domination of the spice trade. The Europeans established small settlements, and in many of them the European residents were all men. Without contact with Dutch women, they began turning to their female slaves (mostly originating from [[Sulawesi]], [[Bali]], and outside the archipelago) for sexual services. By 1620 the habit had become so prevalent that [[List of Governors-General of the Dutch East Indies|Governor-General]] [[Jan Pieterszoon Coen]] passed a law forbidding Dutchmen from keeping concubines.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=1–2}} To prevent a relapse, Coen began bringing orphans from the Netherlands, termed ''compagniesdochters'', to become wives of company employees.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=2–3}}<!--insert note/link about les Filles du Roi in New France--> The program, however, had little effect, as the company could not keep up with the demand. There were also concerns that these women were only accepting marriage for personal gain and that they would attempt to draw their husbands back to the Netherlands&nbsp;– and out of the employment of the Dutch East Indies Company.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=2–3}}
In the 1650s, Governors-General [[Carel Reyniersz]] and [[Joan Maetsuycker]] began promoting interracial marriage between Dutchmen and [[native Indonesians|indigenous]] women, who were thought to be less greedy and less likely to ask their husbands to leave the Indies. The [[Indo people|Eurasian]] daughters of these marriages proved to be popular targets of affections, as marriage to one could help men improve their social position.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=3–5}} Many men, however, were unable to marry them, as they generally sought persons already in a position of power. Instead, it was more common for Dutchmen to take Asian women as their partners, as they could not marry without the company's permission and would not be repatriated if they married a non-Christian.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=9–10}}
When the British took control of the Indies in 1812, they were shocked by the practices of concubinage, interracial marriages, and slavery in the Indies. They attempted to force all elements of Indies society to live in accordance with British morals. However, they were unable to eliminate the keeping of ''njais'', and, indeed, some Englishmen kept a ''njai'' of their own.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=15–17}}
After the British returned the Indies to the Dutch in 1815, a new wave of immigration&nbsp;– including some women&nbsp;– began. These newcomers, as with the British before them, were shocked by the intermarriage and keeping of ''njais''. Under the new system they established, which pushed for a sharper delineation between Europeans and non-Europeans, a ''njai'' marrying a European could be recognized as of a similar stature to Europeans. Those who were not married, however, received no special recognition.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=19–20}}
Owing to an economic boom, the early 20th century saw another surge in immigration from Europe. With the European population now of a considerable size, Indies society began drifting towards a more racially divided one. Venues exclusive to one racial group were opened, and European, Chinese, and indigenous people rarely intermingled. Along with this change, the position of men living with a ''njai'' became increasingly difficult. The Indies government, following a decree by Governor-General [[Alexander Willem Frederik Idenburg]], would not hire them, and businesses attempted to promote [[endogamy]]. In the Netherlands, extensive polemics were written which condemned, from a moral point of view, the practice of keeping a ''njai'': the practice was deemed to be based on nothing but lust, for a ''njai'' "could not touch the soul". Concern was also expressed over men's seeming lack of enthusiasm for having children with their ''njai'', leading to high abortion rates.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=86}}
By the 1910s the number of ''njais'' had decreased, although [[prostitution in Indonesia|prostitution]] had become more prevalent.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=87}} The practice had not died out, however, by the time the [[Empire of Japan]] invaded and [[Japanese occupation of the Dutch East Indies|occupied]] the Indies. During the occupation, the ''njai'' and their mixed-race children were forcefully separated from European men, who were put into internment camps.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=223}} After the occupation ended in 1945, [[Sukarno]] [[proclamation of Indonesian Independence|proclaimed]] an independent Indonesia. During the ensuing [[Indonesian National Revolution|revolution]], the ''njai'' were forced to choose between going with their partners to Europe, or staying in Indonesia; both choices were taken.{{sfn|Baay|2010|pp=224–25}}
==Rights and social status== The ''njai'' could be sent home with little or no warning,{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=1}} with or without her children. This was common when the European man prepared to marry.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=10}}
The general view of ''njai'' was, at first, extremely negative. In the 17th century, they were described as "lustful beasts", with voracious sexual appetites who would not accept money for sex, but pay for it. Coen, in a 1620 letter, described ''njai'' as lazy (except in their sexual deeds), stupid, dishonest, and willing to kill the persons they hated.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=12}}
==Children== The children of a ''njai'' were often raised in indigenous traditions, by their mother or by a maid. The fathers would generally not interact with them, preferring to socialize with other European men instead.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=10}} In the 17th century few could speak Dutch, although later education programs were initiated to promote the use of the language.{{sfn|Baay|2010|p=11}}
==In culture== [[File:Njai Dasima p103.jpg|thumb|Poster for ''[[Njai Dasima (1929 film)|Njai Dasima]]'' (1929)]] ===Literature=== The ''njai'' has a broad presence in literature. James Siegel argues that "Dutch shame", which he describes as caused by guilt over the contemporary situation in the Indies that the Dutch colonialists seemed incapable of improving, gave rise to certain stock characters that would explain Dutch political and administrative failure. Siegel cites such characters as the "venal Arab" and the "lustful, greedy Chinese merchant", and the "'deceitful' housekeeper or ''njai''".<ref name="Siegel1997">{{cite book|last=Siegel|first=James T.|title=Fetish, Recognition, Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JOqVuLrIGycC&pg=PA60|year=1997|publisher=Princeton UP|isbn=9780691026527|pages=38–39}}</ref>
''Njai'' characters are common in works of [[Chinese Malay literature]]. Some of the earliest were ''[[syair]]'' (poems), published in 1907 by [[Lie Kim Hok]] and Tjiang O. S. respectively in 1897; both were adaptations of ''Tjerita Njai Dasima''.{{sfn|Salmon|1985|p=30}} In 1904, Oei Soei Tiong published ''Njai Alimah''.{{sfn|Salmon|1985|pp=48–49}} In the 1910s and 1920s, several books were published with ''njais'' as the title characters, including ''Njai Aisah'' (Tan Boen Kim; 1915), ''Njai Soemirah'' ([[Thio Tjin Boen]]; 1917), and ''Njai Marsina'' (Numa, 1923).{{sfn|Salmon|1985|p=60}}
===Film=== ''Njai'' are present in early films from the Dutch East Indies, several of which were adapted from novels. In 1929 [[Tan's Film]] produced ''[[Njai Dasima (1929 film)|Njai Dasima]]'', an adaptation of ''Tjerita Njai Dasima''. The film was a critical and commercial success, and Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] writes that cinemas could make up for several days of losses with a single showing.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=24}} ''Tjerita Njai Dasima'' has since been adapted a further three times. A [[Njai Dasima (1932 film)|talkie version]], directed by [[Bachtiar Effendi]], was released by Tan's by January 1932.<ref>{{cite news |title=(untitled) |work=[[De Indische Courant]] |language=Dutch |page=14 |location=Surabaya |date=14 January 1932 |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/article/id/ddd%3A010283820%3Ampeg21%3Ap014%3Aa0072 }}</ref> Although the [[Dasima (film)|1941 adaptation]] eliminated Dasima's role as a ''njai'',{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=242–43}} the 1970 adaptation ''[[Samiun and Dasima]]'' by Hasmanan reinstated Dasima's role as a ''njai''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/title/lf-s015-70-027704_samiun-dan-dasima |title=Samiun dan Dasima |language=Indonesian |work=filmindonesia.or.id |publisher=Konfiden Foundation |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NcElBKPw |archivedate=24 February 2014 |accessdate=24 February 2014}}</ref> Other Indies films featuring ''njai'' in key roles include ''[[Boenga Roos dari Tjikembang (1931 film)|Boenga Roos dari Tjikembang]]'' (1931) and ''[[De Stem des Bloeds]]'' (1932); the latter of these has been read as promoting a positive image of the mixed-race children of ''njai'' and Europeans.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=124, 126}}
